In the [[Book of Exodus]], '''Amram''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|æ|m|r|æ|m}}) is the husband of [[Jochebed]] and father of [[Aaron]], [[Moses]] and [[Miriam]].<ref>{{bibleverse||Exodus|6:20|}}</ref>  

Alternative spellings of the name include {{Hebrew Name|עַמְרָם|‘Amram|ʻAmrām|"Friend of the most high"{{\}}"The people are exalted"}}.

== In the Bible ==

In addition to being married to Jochebed, Amram is also described in the Bible as having been related to Jochebed prior to the marriage, although the exact relationship is uncertain; some Greek and Latin manuscripts of the [[Septuagint]] state that Jochebed was Amram's father's cousin, and others state that Amram was Jochebed's cousin,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ecmarsh.com/lxx-kjv/exodus/exo_006.htm|title=Exodus Chapter 6|website=www.ecmarsh.com|accessdate=September 2, 2019}}</ref> but the [[Masoretic Text]] states that she was his father's sister.<ref>''[[New American Bible]]'', footnote to Exodus 6:20</ref>  He is praised for his faith in the [[Epistle to the Hebrews]].<ref>{{Bibleref||Hebrews|11:23}}</ref>

Textual scholars attribute the biblical genealogy to the [[Book of Generations]], a hypothetically reconstructed document theorized to originate from a similar [[wiktionary:religiopolitical|religiopolitical]] group and date to the [[priestly source]].<ref>[[Richard Elliott Friedman]], ''Who Wrote The Bible?''</ref> According to [[Biblical criticism|critical scholars]], the Torah's genealogy for Levi's descendants, is actually an [[aetiology|aetiological]] [[myth]] reflecting the fact that there were four different groups among the [[Levites]] – the [[Gershonites]], [[Kohathites]], [[Merarites]], and [[Kohen|Aaronid]]s;<ref name = "wnsmyy">''[[Peake's Commentary on the Bible]]''</ref> Aaron – the eponymous ancestor of the Aaronids – could not be portrayed as a brother to [[Gershon]], [[Kohath]], and [[Merari]], as the narrative about the birth of Moses (brother of Aaron), which textual scholars attribute to the earlier [[Elohist]] source, mentions only that ''both'' his parents were Levites (without identifying their names).<ref>{{Bibleverse||Exodus|2:1–2|}}</ref> Critical scholars suspect that the Elohist account offers both [[matrilinear descent|matrilineal]] and [[patrilinear descent|patrilineal]] descent from Levites in order to magnify the religious credentials of Moses.<ref name = "wnsmyy"/>

== Arabic ==
''Amram'' in Arabic is spelled ''‘Imrān'' ({{IPAc-en|ɪ|m|ˈ|r|ɑː|n}}, {{lang-ar|عِمْرَانُ}}), was the husband of [[Jochebed in Islam|Jochebed]] and father of Moses and Aaron. As mentioned by his given name, Mûsâ ibn Imran, which means Moses is a son of Imran. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wbg1AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA52#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=A History of Jewish-Muslim Relations: From the Origins to the Present Day|first1=Abdelwahab|last1=Meddeb|first2=Benjamin|last2=Stora|date=November 27, 2013|publisher=Princeton University Press|accessdate=September 2, 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>

